us people and people of color are leading the way against the greatest threat to our environment: the fossil fuel industry. Their stories and movements-in the real world and through science fiction-help us all better understand the relationship between activism and culture, and how both can be valuable tools in creating our future. Imagining the Future of Climate Change introduces readers to the history and most significant flashpoints in climate justice through speculative fictions and social movements, exploring post-disaster possibilities and the art of world-making.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aClimatic changes. 0aGlobal warming. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzUnited States. 4abiologist. 4aclimate change. 4aclimate justice. 4adigital media. 4aecologist. 4aimpact of global warming. 4amarine biologist. 4apreservation. 4ascience fiction. 4asustainability. 4asustainable lifestyle. 4awhat happens during climate change. 70(DE-601)1042881160(DE-588)4164199-1aKlimaänderung2gnd 70(DE-601)1042889220(DE-588)4026718-0aIndianer2gnd 70(DE-601)1057744560(DE-588)4120730-0aMigration2gnd 70(DE-601)1554809600(DE-588)4344515-9aErwärmunggMeteorologie2gnd 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520967557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520967557.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 20